      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <supplied reason="lost">Hic req</supplied>
               <unclear>u</unclear>iescit in pace
                <lb n="2"/>
               <supplied reason="lost">famu</supplied>lus Dei <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Paulus">Paulus</name>
               </persName> diac<hi rend="tall">o</hi>nus,
                <lb n="3"/> qui bixit <expan><abbr>an</abbr><ex>n</ex><abbr>us</abbr></expan>
               <expan><abbr>pl</abbr><ex>u</ex><abbr><hi rend="small">s</hi></abbr></expan>
               <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>inu</ex><abbr>s</abbr></expan>
               <num xml:lang="lat" value="20">
                  <hi rend="ligature">XX</hi>
               </num>,
                <lb n="4"/> depositus SDS <num xml:lang="lat" value="9">VIIII</num>
               <expan><abbr>Kal</abbr><ex>endas</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>Dec</abbr><ex>em</ex><abbr>br</abbr><ex>es</ex></expan>.</ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>[Here res]ts in peace Paulus, a [serv]ant of God (and) a deacon, who lived more or less for twenty years 
                      (and) was laid (here) on the ninth day before? --- the Kalends of December.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 3: "anus" for "annos".</p>
            <p>Line 4: The expansion of SDS is unclear. EDR suggests that the SD be
               expanded into "s(ub) d(ie)", which is a common component of the dating formula used
               in this inscription but does not account for the second S. The second S is distinct
               in style from the first S and resembles the S's of the abbreviated "pl(u)s m(inu)s" in line
               3, suggesting that the DS in line 4 may also be an abbreviation. </p>
         </div>
